               <p>182. <persName id="def1-182-18491126" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-182-18491126" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-182-18491126" type="age" value="31"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-182-18491126" type="surname" value="WHALE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-182-18491126" type="given" value="MICHAEL"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">MICHAEL WHALE</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18491126-182-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18491126-182-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18491126-182-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>, stealing 43 pairs of boots and 12 pairs of shoes, value 9<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 11<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; the property of <persName id="t18491126-name-1057" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1057" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1057" type="surname" value="LION"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1057" type="given" value="ABRAHAM JACOB"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18491126-182-offence-1 t18491126-name-1057"></join>Abraham Jacob Lion</persName>, and another.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-1058" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1058" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1058" type="surname" value="LION"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1058" type="given" value="ABRAHAM JACOB"></interp>ABRAHAM JACOB LION</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a shoe-warehouse, in Crown-street, Fins-bury. In the beginning of July, the prisoner called and gave an order to my brother, who is my partner, to send some boots and shoes to 34, Lisle-street, Kent-road—we said we could not send them unless he paid or lefts deposit—he promised that he would call again in the afternoon, but he did not—in a fortnight afterwards he called again, and gave us a fresh order, and we were to send the goods next day—he left ten shillings deposit—we sent them, and desired the porter not to leave them without the balance of the money—we did not consider the deposit as part payment—we did not like to send the goods at all—we gave the porter directions several times not to leave them without the money; and when he was gone, 1 sent after him to say so.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I left a deposit of ten shillings, and took a receipt of him; he did not send them all, only a part, and part of them were wrong.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> The porter went back the same evening to bring the goods or the money—I went myself at twelve o'clock at night; I saw the prisoner; I wanted the goods back, or the money; he would not do so—I said I would give him the ten shillings back again—I did not have him taken up, because I did not know the law—I saw another case in the newspaper, and then I had him taken on this—I saw no appearance of a shoe-shop, or shoe-business</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184911260181"></xptr>
               <p>there—we wanted to hate him taken, but onr lawyer spoke about the ton shillings, and consulted Mr. Wood about it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-1059" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1059" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1059" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1059" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN JONES</persName>
                  </hi>. I took three dozen and a half of short boots, and one dozen and a half of slippers to the prisoner's house, and knocked at the door—I asked a little boy if Mr. Whale lived there—he said, "Yes"—the prisoner opened the parlour door, and said, "Bring them in"—he opened them, and found there were four pairs short, and he found fault with four pain; he said to me, "Take these back, and bring four pairs of others"—I said I could not leave the goods without the money—he said," You can't take these back; take these four pairs back"—he insisted on my going back with them, and said, "Can you come back this evening?"—I said, "I don't think I can"—he said, "Come in the morning by eleven o'clock, I will wait at home for you"—I went to my master and told him—he gave me four pairs of others for what I brought back, and the other four which were short—I went back, and saw the prisoner; he said, "I did not think you would come back to<lb></lb>night"—I said I did not think I could—I said I must have the money or the goods—he said, "I can't give you the Others back, I have taken the trouble to size them and brush them, to send in the morning"—he took those that I brought, and took the invoice from me—he said he could not give me the goods back—I said I could not leave them—he brought me out a chair to sit down—he said, "You can sit there as long as you like: I shan't turn you out"—he said he should not give me the goods back, nor the money, if I called at eleven in the morning be would pay me—I stopped an hour—I asked him for the invoice to take back with me—he said he should not give it me back, and I was obliged to leave the house without anything—I went to my master's, and told him—my father was there; he wanted to know why I stopped so long—I asked my father to go with me—my father, my master and I, all went together—my father knocked at the door—the prisoner's wife came, and said, "Who is there?"—my father said, "Me"—the prisoner came down, and opened the door—we all went in—the goods were lying on the banisters—my master said he wanted the goods or the money—the prisoner said he would not pay to-night, he would call in the morning and pay.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did not I say you might take the goods back that night if you liked? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">HORNSBT</hi>. I am a pawnbroker—I have some boots I took in of the prisoner, one pair on the 6<hi rend="italic">th</hi>, one pair on 8<hi rend="italic">th</hi>, and one pair on 11<hi rend="italic">th</hi> Oct. <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LION</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> These are part of what were sent on the occa<lb></lb>sion, and what the prisoner ordered.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-1060" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1060" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1060" type="surname" value="YOUNG"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-1060" type="given" value="CHARLES BERESFORD"></interp>CHARLES BERESFORD YOUNG</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker—the prisoner pawned a pair of boots with me on 2<hi rend="italic">nd</hi> Aug., another pair on 28<hi rend="italic">th</hi> Aug., two pairs on 29<hi rend="italic">th</hi> Oct., and one pair on 8<hi rend="italic">th</hi> Nov.—the prosecutor has seen them and identified them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-1061" type="witnessName">
